MVP

Using the dataset austen_books() from the package janeaustenr:

  1. Find the most common words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility.
# Change Pride & Prejudice into a tibble of words;

pride_book <- tibble(
  id = 1:length(prideprejudice),
  text = prideprejudice) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) 
pride_book %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)


# and repeat for Sense & Sensibility

sense_book <- tibble(
  id = 1:length(sensesensibility),
  text = sensesensibility) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) 
sense_book %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
NA
NA

The most common words in Pride and Prejudice and Sense and Sensibility are stop words.

  1. Find the most common words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility, not including stop words.

Stop words can be removed by anti-joining the stop_words lexicon;


pride_book %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
sense_book %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
  1. Find the most common sentiment words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility.

Using the bing lexicon;

pride_sentiment <- pride_book %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word") %>%  # inner_join to avoid NAs
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
pride_sentiment

The top word is miss, but this is a term of address rather than something having been missed, so can be removed;

pride_sentiment <- pride_book %>%
  filter(word!= "miss") %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word") %>%  # inner_join to avoid NAs
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
pride_sentiment

and the same for Sense and Sensibility

sense_sentiment <- sense_book %>% 
  filter(word != "miss") %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word") %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
sense_sentiment

2 Extension

Taking your results above. Can you create a plot which visualises the differences between the books?

Probably best to run a comparison of sentences, rather than words;

sentiment_scores %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = sentence, y = mean_sentiment, colour = book) +
  geom_point(colour = "grey80", alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(title = "Mean Sentence Sentiment Comparison of 
       Pride and Prejudice v Sense and Sensibility",
       x = "Sentence No.",
       y = "Mean Sentiment Score (afinn)",
       colour = "Book")
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The plot shows that both books score very similar results for sentiment on average, with Pride and Prejudice possibly having a happier ending than Sense and Sensibility. The mean remains above 0 for the duration of the books, so the good sentiments outweigh the bad.

Looking at total sentiment scores;

sentiment_scores %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = sentence, y = total_sentiment, colour = book) +
  geom_point(colour = "grey80", alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(title = "Total Sentence Sentiment Comparison of 
       Pride and Prejudice v Sense and Sensibility",
       x = "Sentence No.",
       y = "Total Sentiment Score (afinn)",
       colour = "Book")
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The total sentiment score between the books is closer, but once agani Pride and Prejudice appears to finish on a slightly happier note.
